{"summary":"I would reject fr-7-f5efd49b because its core premise about reqwest timeout semantics is incorrect, and accept fr-7-144385ef plus fr-7-9872eaf7 because both describe concrete, code-verified defects in timeout enforcement and retry classification.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-7-f5efd49b","decision":"reject","rationale":"OpenRouterBackendAdapter does set `reqwest::Client::builder().timeout(request.timeout)` and then awaits both `.send()` and `response.text()`. In reqwest, `ClientBuilder::timeout()` is a total request deadline, applied from connection start until the response body finishes; the per-read reset behavior belongs to `read_timeout()` (https://docs.rs/reqwest/latest/reqwest/struct.ClientBuilder.html). That means a slow trickle-streaming response is still bounded by the configured timeout, so `enforces_timeout() == true` is consistent with the adapter’s documented behavior. The amendment’s proposed defect depends on a timeout semantic that reqwest does not use here."},{"amendment_id":"fr-7-144385ef","decision":"accept","rationale":"TmuxAdapter advertises `enforces_timeout() == true` by delegating to ProcessBackendAdapter, but its `invoke()` path never applies `request.timeout`. It only calls `build_command()` on the process adapter and then waits in `wait_for_session_exit()`, which is an unbounded polling loop until the service cancels it. Because AgentExecutionService adds a 30-second buffer whenever `enforces_timeout()` is true, tmux invocations can run about 30 seconds past the configured timeout before the safety-net timeout fires. That is a real timeout-enforcement regression in tmux mode."},{"amendment_id":"fr-7-9872eaf7","decision":"accept","rationale":"`OpenRouterBackendAdapter::api_key()` reports a missing `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` as `BackendUnavailable { failure_class: None }`. `AppError::failure_class()` maps that to `TransportFailure`, and the retry policy retries transport failures up to 5 times. A missing API key is a deterministic prerequisite failure, not a transient transport issue, so the current classification wastes retries and delays the real error. The repository already documents and uses `BinaryNotFound` as the terminal class for missing infrastructure prerequisites, including missing API keys in the process backend, so this standalone OpenRouter path is inconsistent and defective."}]}